<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-136-261 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 820 168</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 3 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New advances in material sciences announced. (research fromVanderbilt University and MIT)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCormick, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Optical ComputersIntegrated Circuit FabricationReportsVanderbilt UniversityMassachusetts Institute of Technology. Lincoln LaboratoryLasers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NEW ADVANCES IN MATERIAL SCIENCES ANNOUNCED 06/03/91 WASHINGTON, D.C.,andO;U.S.A., 1991 JUN 3 (NB) -- Science News for May 25 reports several advancesin materials technology related to computer research.andP;  The BaltimoreConference on Lasers and Electro-Optics and the Quantum Electronics and LaserScience Conference are the sources of the reports, the first of whichexamines the use of a series of low-power laser pulses to selectively meltconnecting &quot;wires&quot; on integrated-circuit chips.andM;The research, conducted by MIT Lincoln Lab scientists, shows thatlower-powered pulses cause less damage to adjacent areas on the chips butstill do the job previously done with higher-powered laser systems.andM;A report from Vanderbilt U. shows a possible way to produce thin films oflithium niobate, a photo-refractive crystal that could be used in opticalcomputer circuits.andM;IBM researchers have developed the first polymer which shows aphoto-refractive effect similar to that of lithium niobate and may lead tomuch less expensive optical computer components such as holographic datastorage.andM;All of this is at the research stage, with no products on the horizon, butthe ongoing developments indicate that American companies are still strivingto maintain a technological lead.andM;(John McCormick/19910531)</TEXT></DOC>